@node play "The game: Installation/Playing"

                             Installation

  The installation is very simple, just place "GoFigure" where you
want on your hard drive, floppy disk, Ram Disk, etc. No other files
or Libraries are needed.

                             How to play?

  GoFigure is a Workbench game played on a 11 by 11 tile board.
At the start of a game there are 9 tiles placed in the center of
the board, these tiles have shapes consisting of angles, vertical
or horizontal lines. The goal is create closed figures using the
available shapes on the board.

  To play, just click on a tile, its shape will rotate clockwise
by 90 degrees. To create figures, a shape must 'connect' with the
shapes of it's neighbouring tiles, in order to create a path. To
close a figure, that path must return to a tile, where the path
was started. When a figure is completed, it is removed from the
board.

  The bigger the figure you make, the more points you will get
(obviously). For example: a figure made with 4 tiles will give you
1 point, but a figure made with 6 tiles will be worth 4 points.
The score adds up exponentially as shown in the following table:

  Number of tiles        Points
         4                   1
         6                   4
         8                  16
        16                 144
        32                 784
        64                3600
       120               13456

  If you rotate a tile and it doesn't complete a figure, a new
tile will be added to the board. That new tile will always be
placed next to another tile, so by its orientation, it may
complete a figure, if that happens, the figure will be removed
but you will get no points for it. When tiles add up, be careful
that the board doesn't fill up completely, because when the board
is full, the game is over.

  As you progress in the game, in addition to the normal tiles,
some tiles will rotate randomly or one of the following tiles may
appear from time to time:

@{b}Joker tile@{ub}:     This tile, represented by 4 little squares that
                are placed so they make a cross shape, can act as any
                normal tile. This is handy if you need a specific tile
                to complete a figure. You must click on the tile in
                order to 'activate' it. Note that there will be only one
                Joker tile at any time.

@{b}Fixed tile@{ub}:     This tile, as its name suggests, is fixed (or
                'pressed down') on the game board, so you cannot
                rotate it, otherwise, it is just like a normal tile.

@{b}Explosive tile@{ub}: This tile can be used to eliminate some tiles
                around it, so it can be handy if you want to remove some
                unwanted tiles. You get 1 point for each removed tile.
                Note that you have to click on it to make it explode,
                and like the Joker tile, there is only one Explosive
                tile at a time.

@{b}Brick tile@{ub}:     This tile has a brick-wall drawing, it has only
                one purpose: complicating the game, as you cannot
                use or eliminate it (other than with an Explosive
                tile).

  A Top 10 records the best scores and number of completed figures
made, when there are same scores, the @{b}least@{ub} number of figures made
will be placed higher.

